<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-179  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 179.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  Jan 1990 v9 n1 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FOG-M's slow march from basement to battlefield. (the FiberopticGuided Missile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrison, David C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Fiberoptic Guided Missile (FOG-M) is meant to be guided intoits targets by a television seeker feeding images to its operatorvia a fiberoptic link as long as several dozen kilometers.andP;  Use offiberoptic light cables allows clear visual information to betransmitted when the FOG-M is fired from a secure, concealedposition; operators can still seek out targets while the missile'loiters' over enemy lines.andP;  Syndicated military affairs columnistFred Reed is enthusiastic about the FOG-M, saying it provides aclear picture of the target, which is usually a tank orhelicopter, and keeps the missile on a steady course.andP;  The FOG-Mdevelopment program was allotted $96.5 million in FY 1989, willreceive $139.4 million in FY 1990 and is expected to receive $98.3million in FY 1991; controversies surrounding the program, part ofthe US Army's $2.9 billion Non-Line Of Sight (NLOS) program, arediscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     WeaponsFiber OpticsTechnologyNew TechniqueResearch and DevelopmentMilitaryGovernment FundingMissilesUnited States. Army.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>